For y\in A, the counit requires x \wedge (x \to y) \le y. Notice that by construction, x_i \to _i y_i \le a_i. This way, using the counit of each \to _i, we have
\begin {align*} x \wedge (x_i \to _i y_i) &= x \wedge a_i \wedge (x_i \to _i y_i) \\ &= x_i \wedge (x_i \to _i y_i) \\ &\le x_i \wedge y_i \end {align*}
It follows that x \wedge (x \to y) = \bigvee _{i\in I} x \wedge (x_i \to _i y_i) \le \bigvee _{i\in I}x_i \wedge y_i \le y.

If \mathcal {O}_{X} is a Heyting algebra, then we have an explicit morphism
 (-) \to  (-) : \mathcal {O}_{X}^{\mathrm {op}} \times  \mathcal {O}_{X} \to  \mathcal {O}_{X} 
over X. This induces an implication operator on each affine open \operatorname {Spec} A of X, which must be the implication operator, since when we have a function symbol, being the implication operator is an equational property. This implies X must be Heyting.

  For a class of maps between schemes, we say it is affine admissible, if 

It is closed under compositions and pullbacks;

It is affine local on the target.

  For (2) \Leftrightarrow  (3), we know the map \downarrow  x \to  \downarrow  fx dually corresponds to the map f^{-1}(I)/D \to  I/E, where I is the complement prime ideal of x, induced as follows (cf. Lemma ),

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
    \begin {tikzcd}
      D \ar [d, two heads] \ar [r] & E \ar [d, two heads] \\ 
      f^{-1}(I)/D \ar [r] & I/E
    \end {tikzcd}


  Now by Proposition , \downarrow  x \to  \downarrow  fx is injective iff the corresponding algebraic map is an epimorphism, which is exactly the definition of relative Boolean algebra.

Here we discuss some examples of separated and non-separated affine schemes. For a positive example, consider the following map between finite affine schemes,
\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver} \begin {tikzcd} \bullet && \bullet & \bullet \\ & \bullet && \bullet \arrow [curve={height=-18pt}, dashed, from=1-1, to=1-4] \arrow [dashed, from=1-3, to=1-4] \arrow [from=2-2, to=1-1] \arrow [from=2-2, to=1-3] \arrow [dashed, from=2-2, to=2-4] \arrow [from=2-4, to=1-4] \end {tikzcd}
which corresponds to the distributive lattice morphism x \mapsto y \vee z : 2[x] \to y \wedge z/2[y,z] By the characterisation in Proposition , this map is separated.

On the other hand, the "dual" case as follows,
\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver} \begin {tikzcd} & \bullet && \bullet \\ \bullet && \bullet & \bullet \arrow [dashed, from=1-2, to=1-4] \arrow [from=2-1, to=1-2] \arrow [curve={height=18pt}, dashed, from=2-1, to=2-4] \arrow [from=2-3, to=1-2] \arrow [dashed, from=2-3, to=2-4] \arrow [from=2-4, to=1-4] \end {tikzcd}
which corresponds to the map x \mapsto y \wedge z : 2[x] \to 2[y,z]/y\vee z is not separated. Though it still have Stone fibres (cf. Remark ).

